          { type: 'text', content: '<p>Look at those bowling numbers. Powerplay economy improved by a full run per over. Middle-overs economy dropped from 9.53 to 8.89. Yes, batting strike rates came down across every phase (especially at the death, from 195.9 to 180.8), but that\'s the point. RCB stopped trying to win shootouts and started winning chess matches.</p>' },
          { type: 'text', content: '<p><strong>Squad-Building Philosophy:</strong> RCB has gone from stacking batting talent like it\'s going out of fashion to investing in bowling infrastructure. The retention of Bhuvneshwar (10.75 Cr), Hazlewood (12.50 Cr), and Krunal (5.75 Cr), three of the four priciest bowler retentions, tells you everything. They\'re top-heavy with the bat (Kohli + Salt own the powerplay; David + Jitesh own the death), lean in the middle order, and deep with bowling options. Five all-rounders (Venkatesh Iyer, Krunal, Shepherd, Bethell, Swapnil Singh) suggest a belief in flexibility over specialization. This is a franchise that has finally learned what every successful team already knows: you can\'t buy a title with batters alone. Someone has to actually get the other lot out.</p>' }
