          { type: 'text', content: '<p><strong>Captaincy:</strong> Hardik Pandya (16.35 Cr, retained) continues as captain after a turbulent 2024 and a redemptive 2025. His all-round improvement in 2025 (151.4 batting SR, 9.04 bowling economy) earned him the right to lead this squad into a title push. His challenge is managing the egos of a dressing room that includes Rohit Sharma, the franchise\'s former captain and India\'s most capped T20I player.</p>' },
          { type: 'text', content: '<p><strong>Key Departures (from 2025 squad):</strong> Ishan Kishan (to PBKS), Cameron Green (to KKR), Piyush Chawla (released), Gerald Coetzee (to RR), Tim David (released), Nehal Wadhera (released). The departures strip MI of two things: Kishan\'s wicketkeeping versatility and Green\'s all-round balance at #3. Piyush Chawla\'s 30 wickets at 8.45 economy in the middle overs (78 overs, HIGH) leaves a genuine spin gap that Santner and Markande must fill.</p>' },
          { type: 'text', content: '<p><strong>Key Retentions:</strong> MI retained 14 players totaling 115.30 Cr. The big four are locked: Bumrah (18.00 Cr), Suryakumar Yadav (16.35 Cr), Hardik Pandya (16.35 Cr), and Rohit Sharma (16.30 Cr). The fifth retention was Boult (12.50 Cr), signaling that MI\'s bowling identity is non-negotiable. Deepak Chahar (9.25 Cr) and Tilak Varma (8.00 Cr) round out the premium tier. The retention of AM Ghazanfar (4.80 Cr), a 19-year-old Afghan off-spinner with zero IPL appearances but 34 T20 wickets at 7.2 economy cross-tournament (HIGH trust), is the most intriguing signal in the squad.</p>' },
          { type: 'text', content: '<p><strong>What\'s Structurally Different from 2025:</strong> Two shifts matter. First, the spin composition has changed: Chawla\'s leg-spin (78 middle-overs overs) is replaced by a blend of Santner\'s left-arm orthodox (45 overs, HIGH), Will Jacks\'s off-spin (16 overs, LOW), and the unproven Ghazanfar. MI\'s spin attack is thinner but more varied. Second, the batting lineup gains a left-handed dimension: de Kock, Tilak Varma, Rutherford, and Santner provide four left-hand options where MI previously relied almost entirely on right-handers. The squad is less top-heavy in spin but better balanced in handedness.</p>' }
